{"id":"1809.00124","submitter":"Ken-Ichi Nakao","authors":"Ken-ichi Nakao, Chul-Moon Yoo and Tomohiro Harada","title":"On gravastar formation: What can be the evidence of a black hole?","comments":"44 pages, 17 figures. The discussion on when the gravastar formation\n  starts has been revised in the 4th paragraph of Sec.V","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. D 99, 044027 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.99.044027","report-no":"OCU-PHYS-485, AP-GR-149, RUP-18-28","categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Any observer outside black holes cannot detect any physical signal produced\nby the black holes themselves, since, by definition, the black holes are not\nlocated in the causal past of the outside observer. In fact, what we regard as\nblack hole candidates in our view are not black holes but will be\ngravitationally contracting objects. As well known, a black hole will form by a\ngravitationally collapsing object in the infinite future in the views of\ndistant observers like us. At the very late stage of the gravitational\ncollapse, the gravitationally contracting object behaves as a black body due to\nits gravity. Due to this behavior, the physical signals produced around it\n(e.g. the quasi-normal ringings and the shadow image) will be very similar to\nthose caused in the eternal black hole spacetime. However those physical\nsignals do not necessarily imply the formation of a black hole in the future,\nsince we cannot rule out the possibility that the formation of the black hole\nis prevented by some unexpected event in the future yet unobserved. As such an\nexample, we propose a scenario in which the final state of the gravitationally\ncontracting spherical thin shell is a gravastar that has been proposed as a\nfinal configuration alternative to a black hole by Mazur and Mottola. This\nscenario implies that time necessary to observe the moment of the gravastar\nformation can be much longer than the lifetime of the pres